data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific asserts that give better failure messages than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's an improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreNotEqual(0, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** — on failure reports `Expected:<3>. Actual:<5>` instead of just `Assert.IsTrue failed`
- **`Assert.AreNotEqual(0, ...)`** — clearer intent than `IsTrue(x > 0)`
- **Add messages to `IsTrue`** calls so failures are diagnosable
- **`users.Any()`** instead of `Single()` — avoids throwing `InvalidOperationException` before the assert even runs

**Other useful tools:**

| Scenario | Use |
|---|---|
| Check items exist | `CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser)` |
| Compare two lists | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` (order matters) |
| Same items, any order | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` |
| Type checking | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User))` |
| No nulls | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users)` |
| Uniqueness | `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users)` |

For complex assertions, consider the **FluentAssertions** NuGet package which gives you expressive syntax like `users.Should().HaveCount(3).And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`.
